## Drift Analysis

{% if drift.b_failed_count == 0 -%}
No drift detected. All workflows pass Comparison B (drifted inputs), indicating the projection engine is robust to input distribution changes.
{% else -%}
{{ drift.b_failed_count }} of {{ drift.total }} workflows failed Comparison B (drifted inputs).

**Diagnosis: {{ drift.diagnosis | replace("_", " ") | title }}**

{% if drift.diagnosis == "tier_weight_shift" -%}
All workflows degrade similarly under drift, suggesting a tier weight shift rather than workflow-specific issues. The input distribution has shifted uniformly across complexity tiers. This is the most common and most addressable form of drift -- `--traffic-mix` reweighting should resolve it.
{% elif drift.diagnosis == "style_shift_loops" -%}
Failures are concentrated in loop-based workflows. The drifted inputs likely trigger different loop iteration counts than the profiling inputs. This is a style shift: the new inputs exercise loops differently (longer chains, more retries, or different termination conditions).
{% elif drift.diagnosis.startswith("style_shift_") -%}
Failures are concentrated in {{ drift.concentrated_group }} workflows. The drifted inputs likely exercise these workflow patterns differently than the profiling inputs.
{% elif drift.diagnosis == "mixed_drift" -%}
Failures are spread across workflow groups with varying severity. This suggests multiple drift dimensions are at play. Individual workflow investigation is needed.
{% endif %}

**Failed workflows:** {{ drift.b_failed | join(", ") }}

